        <h2 class="mb-4">An Established Business School</h2>

        <p>
          Management education in Glasgow took off in 1947 when the Royal College of Science and Technology founded its
          Department of Industrial Administration.
        </p>
        <p>
          The Glasgow School of Management followed in 1950, linking the college with the Glasgow and West of Scotland
          Commercial College. When both merged in 1964 to form the University of Strathclyde, a new School of Business
          and Administration emerged, quickly building a reputation for innovation and launching
          <strong>Scotland's first MBA in 1966</strong>.
        </p>

        <img class="d-md-none d-sm-block mb-sm-4" src="./images/old-school.jpg" alt="Old Photo">

        <p>
          In 1971, Strathclyde joined forces with other Scottish universities to create the Scottish Business School,
          paving the way for the founding of Strathclyde Business School in 1973.
        </p>
        <p>
          A restructuring in 1982 turned it into a full faculty, uniting business education under one banner and
          cementing Strathclyde's role as a pioneer of Scottish management education.
        </p>

        <p>
          <a class="btn btn-primary btn-lg mt-3" href="#timeline">See our timeline</a>
        </p>
